<section class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-inner">
        <div class="faq-left">
            <p class="titan-section-label">COMMON QUESTIONS</p>
            <h2 class="faq-heading">Retirement Tax FAQ</h2>
            <p class="faq-sub">Everything you need to know about reducing taxes in retirement.</p>
            <a href="/contact/" class="resources-cta">Get Tax Strategy Review</a>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-right">
            <div class="faq-accordion">
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Are Roth conversions worth it?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">It depends on your current tax bracket, future tax bracket, and time horizon. Roth conversions work best during low-income years (after retirement but before Social Security starts) or when you're in lower tax brackets than you expect to be later. We model your specific situation to determine if and when Roth conversions make sense. Consult with a tax professional for advice specific to your circumstances.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">How is Social Security taxed?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Up to 85% of your Social Security benefits can be taxed at the federal level depending on your combined income (adjusted gross income + tax-exempt interest + 50% of Social Security). The more other income you have, the more of your Social Security gets taxed. Strategic withdrawal planning and Roth conversions can help minimize Social Security taxation.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">What is IRMAA?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">IRMAA (Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount) is a Medicare surcharge for higher earners. If your modified adjusted gross income exceeds certain thresholds (starting at $106,000 for individuals, $212,000 for couples in 2025), you pay extra for Medicare Part B and Part D. These surcharges can add $500-$6,000+ per year. We help you manage income to avoid or minimize IRMAA.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">When do RMDs start?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Required Minimum Distributions (RMDs) from traditional IRAs and 401(k)s start at age 73 (for those born 1951-1959) or age 75 (for those born 1960 or later) under current law. RMDs are taxable income whether you need the money or not. Roth IRAs do not have RMDs during the owner's lifetime, which is one reason Roth conversions can be valuable.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">How can I reduce taxes on my 401(k) withdrawals?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Several strategies can help: withdraw strategically to stay within lower tax brackets, do Roth conversions during low-income years, coordinate withdrawals with Social Security timing to minimize taxation of benefits, consider Qualified Charitable Distributions (QCDs) if you're charitably inclined, and optimize the order you tap different account types (taxable, tax-deferred, Roth). We build a customized withdrawal strategy based on your specific situation. Strategies may vary based on individual circumstances — consult with a tax professional.</div>
                </button>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
